# .env.local.example — reference for environment variables used by this devcontainer.
# .env.local is gitignored — never commit your keys.
#
# HOW THIS WORKS:
#   devcontainer.json uses ${localEnv:VAR_NAME} to read variables from your HOST
#   environment (the shell where you run VS Code). These are NOT loaded from this
#   file automatically — you must export them in your shell first.
#
# To set these variables:
#   Option A (per-session): export them before opening VS Code:
#     export COPILOT_BYOK_API_KEY=sk-...
#     code .
#
#   Option B (permanent): add them to your shell profile (~/.bashrc, ~/.zshrc,
#     PowerShell $PROFILE, etc.):
#     export COPILOT_BYOK_API_KEY=sk-...
#
#   Option C (direnv): copy this file to .devcontainer/.env.local, fill in values,
#     then use direnv or a similar tool to auto-export on directory entry.
#
# This file lists all variables the devcontainer supports — use it as a reference.

# ── Offline mode ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# Set to "true" to enable COPILOT_OFFLINE — disables network calls.
# Useful in air-gapped or restricted network environments.
# export COPILOT_OFFLINE=true

# ── BYOK (Bring Your Own Key) ─────────────────────────────────────────────────
# Use your own Azure OpenAI, OpenAI-compatible, or local model endpoint.
# Leave unset to use GitHub's default Copilot model.

# Your model API key:
# export COPILOT_BYOK_API_KEY=sk-...

# Your model endpoint (optional — omit to use OpenAI-compatible default):
# Azure OpenAI:        https://<resource>.openai.azure.com/
# OpenAI-compatible:   https://api.openai.com/v1
# Local Ollama:        http://localhost:11434/v1
# export COPILOT_BYOK_ENDPOINT=https://
